tools_called.args:
{"query": "What direct removal techniques are available for controlling invasive American bullfrogs and red-eared terrapins in North American ponds?", "summary": "For American bullfrogs, direct removal techniques include trapping using double fyke nets which were found effective in catching bullfrog tadpoles in small shallow ponds in Belgium (action 1046). Adult bullfrog removal techniques include using single traps floating on the water surface overnight in small ponds in the USA (action 1045), though catchability using double fyke nets was found to be very low. Shooting metamorphosed individuals before reproduction was also used as part of combination treatments in France, resulting in significant reduction in recorded adults and juveniles (action 1045). However, one study found that bullfrog populations rapidly rebounded following intensive removal of adults (action 1045).

For red-eared terrapins, Aranzadi turtle traps were found effective for trapping adults from rivers in Spain, though they did not eradicate the population (action 1055). Sein nets were used to trap adults and juveniles in the British Virgin Islands but were not successful in eradicating the population (action 1055). Draining invaded waterbodies was considered as a removal technique for red-eared terrapins but no evidence was found on its impact on population reduction (action 1057).

Both species showed rapid population recovery following removal efforts, indicating that sustained and repeated removal efforts are necessary for effective control.", "action_ids": ["1045", "1046", "825", "1055", "1057"]}

